europe's tired poor huddled masses self selection and economic outcomes in the age of mass migration siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display europe's tired poor huddled masses self selection and economic outcomes in the age of mass migration type siepr discussion paper 09 029 author s ran abramitzky leah boustan katherine eriksson published 08 1 10 download pdf abstract the age of mass migration 1850 1913 was among the largest migration episodes in history unlike today the united states maintained an open border in this era we compile a novel dataset of norway to us migrants and estimate the return to migration while accounting for migrant selection our first method compares migrants to their brothers who remained in norway our second exploits the fact that under primogeniture older sons in land owning families were less likely to migrate we find that these migrants unhindered by entry restrictions were negatively selected from the sending population and that the return to migration was relatively low stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
